###--- 02_Roles_LITR
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<!DOCTYPE sailpoint PUBLIC "sailpoint.dtd" "sailpoint.dtd">
<!--
  WORKSHOP DEMO ROLE MODEL  (corrected)
  ====================================================================
  LITR = Location IT Role  -> type="it"
  It reaches an identity by TWO paths (both modeled here on purpose):

    PATH 1  DIRECT, by Enterprise Entity (EE) / branch location
            -> the IT role carries its OWN assignment selector.
            -> covers external EBC users who have NO job function.
            -> IIQ tracks this as an ASSIGNED role.

    PATH 2  LINKED, via a job-function Business Role
            -> the Business Role 'requires' the LITR.
            -> when the BR is assigned, the LITR is auto-provisioned with it.
            -> IIQ tracks this as a REQUIRED (detected dependency) role.

  Why model BOTH: on a MOVER (manager -> non-manager, same branch) the BR
  path drops but the direct EE path keeps the LITR. Modeling LITR as
  BR-only would create an access GAP on the mover. The dual path is what
  makes location access stable across job changes.
-->
<sailpoint>

  <!-- ================= LOCATION IT ROLES (LITR) ================= -->
  <!--
    Each LITR is type="it" AND carries an assignment Selector so it can be
    granted DIRECTLY by Enterprise Entity (Path 1). An IT role with an
    assignment selector is an 'assigned' IT role - supported in IIQ.
  -->

  <Bundle name="LITR-Branch-A" type="it" displayName="LITR - Location Branch A">
    <Description>Location IT Role for Branch A. Directly assignable by EE.</Description>
    <Selector>
      <IdentitySelector>
        <MatchExpression>
          <MatchTerm name="entity" value="BRANCH_A"/>
        </MatchExpression>
      </IdentitySelector>
    </Selector>
  </Bundle>

  <Bundle name="LITR-Branch-B" type="it" displayName="LITR - Location Branch B">
    <Description>Location IT Role for Branch B. Directly assignable by EE.</Description>
    <Selector>
      <IdentitySelector>
        <MatchExpression>
          <MatchTerm name="entity" value="BRANCH_B"/>
        </MatchExpression>
      </IdentitySelector>
    </Selector>
  </Bundle>

  <Bundle name="LITR-Branch-C" type="it" displayName="LITR - Location Branch C">
    <Description>Location IT Role for Branch C. Directly assignable by EE.</Description>
    <Selector>
      <IdentitySelector>
        <MatchExpression>
          <MatchTerm name="entity" value="BRANCH_C"/>
        </MatchExpression>
      </IdentitySelector>
    </Selector>
  </Bundle>

  <!-- ================= BUSINESS ROLES (job function) ================= -->
  <!--
    The job-function Business Role 'requires' the location LITR (Path 2).
    'required' = auto-provisioned with the BR, no request/approval = the
    auto-assignment behaviour the workshop wants.

    DEMO NOTE on resolving the RIGHT branch:
      A single BR cannot statically 'require' all three LITRs (that would
      grant all branches). Two clean options:
        (a) per-branch BR variants, each requiring its own LITR  [shown below]
        (b) one BR + an assignment rule that adds the matching LITR by entity
      Option (a) is shown for Branch A so the dependency is visible in the UI.
      Option (b) is in the assignment-rule file as the scalable pattern.
  -->

  <Bundle name="BR-BranchManager-A" type="business"
          displayName="Business Role - Branch Manager (Branch A)">
    <Description>
      Job-function business role for Branch A managers. Requires the Branch A
      Location IT Role, which is therefore auto-provisioned with this BR.
    </Description>
    <Selector>
      <IdentitySelector>
        <MatchExpression and="true">
          <MatchTerm name="isManager" value="Y"/>
          <MatchTerm name="entity" value="BRANCH_A"/>
        </MatchExpression>
      </IdentitySelector>
    </Selector>
    <Requirements>
      <Reference class="sailpoint.object.Bundle" name="LITR-Branch-A"/>
    </Requirements>
  </Bundle>

  <Bundle name="BR-BranchClerk" type="business"
          displayName="Business Role - Branch Clerk (job function)">
    <Description>
      Generic clerk job-function role. Demonstrates a BR that links the LITR
      by ASSIGNMENT RULE (Path 2, scalable variant) rather than a static
      'requires' - see Rule-Link-LITR. Left with no static requirement so the
      rule-driven link is the visible mechanism.
    </Description>
    <Selector>
      <IdentitySelector>
        <MatchExpression>
          <MatchTerm name="jobCode" value="CLERK"/>
        </MatchExpression>
      </IdentitySelector>
    </Selector>
  </Bundle>

</sailpoint>
###03_Rule_AssignLITR.xml

<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<!DOCTYPE sailpoint PUBLIC "sailpoint.dtd" "sailpoint.dtd">
<!--
  WORKSHOP DEMO - LITR assignment rules (corrected for LITR = Location IT Role)
  ============================================================================
  Two rules, covering both paths and both mechanisms you asked to see.

  Rule-Assign-LITR-Direct   PATH 1, BeanShell variant.
        Same effect as the assignment Selectors on the LITRs in file 02,
        expressed as code so the workshop can compare declarative vs scripted.
        Grants the location LITR by Enterprise Entity alone (externals included).

  Rule-Link-LITR            PATH 2, scalable BR->LITR link.
        Instead of a static 'requires' per branch, one rule adds the LITR that
        matches the identity's entity whenever a job-function BR is held.
        This is the answer to the board's "multiple new rules per branch
        opening = administrative burden": ONE rule, add an entity value.
-->
<sailpoint>

  <!-- ===== PATH 1: direct EE assignment, BeanShell variant ===== -->
  <Rule language="beanshell" name="Rule-Assign-LITR-Direct" type="IdentitySelector">
    <Description>
      Returns the Location IT Role for the identity's Enterprise Entity.
      Entity alone - no job-function check - so external EBC users qualify.
      Equivalent to the Selector on each LITR; shown as code for comparison.
    </Description>
    <Source><![CDATA[
      import java.util.ArrayList;
      import java.util.List;

      List litrs = new ArrayList();
      String entity = identity.getStringAttribute("entity");

      if ("BRANCH_A".equals(entity)) litrs.add("LITR-Branch-A");
      else if ("BRANCH_B".equals(entity)) litrs.add("LITR-Branch-B");
      else if ("BRANCH_C".equals(entity)) litrs.add("LITR-Branch-C");

      return litrs;
    ]]></Source>
  </Rule>

  <!-- ===== PATH 2: BR->LITR link, scalable (one rule, all branches) ===== -->
  <Rule language="beanshell" name="Rule-Link-LITR" type="IdentitySelector">
    <Description>
      When the identity holds a job-function Business Role, add the Location
      IT Role matching its entity. One rule serves every branch: a new branch
      opening adds one entity value, not a new rule. Mirrors the diagram's
      red arrow (User -> Business Role -> linked LITR).
    </Description>
    <Source><![CDATA[
      import java.util.ArrayList;
      import java.util.List;
      import sailpoint.object.Bundle;

      List result = new ArrayList();
      String entity = identity.getStringAttribute("entity");

      // does the identity hold any job-function business role?
      boolean hasJobFunctionBR = false;
      if (identity.getAssignedRoles() != null) {
          for (Bundle b : identity.getAssignedRoles()) {
              if ("business".equals(b.getType())) { hasJobFunctionBR = true; break; }
          }
      }

      if (hasJobFunctionBR && entity != null) {
          result.add("LITR-" + entity.replace("BRANCH_", "Branch-"));
      }
      return result;
    ]]></Source>
  </Rule>

</sailpoint>
---04_Scopes_and_populations.xml

<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<!DOCTYPE sailpoint PUBLIC "sailpoint.dtd" "sailpoint.dtd">
<!--
  WORKSHOP DEMO - The mobility / scoping tradeoff (the orange-flag risk)
  ====================================================================
  The board's tension:
    "If LITR is scoped to Entity of the branch then no people from outside
     this entity can have it -> cannot fulfill mobility/flexibility."
    "If LITR is NOT scoped but open to a larger scope -> anyone can request
     access -> risk."

  KEY IIQ DISTINCTION (this resolves the tension):
    SCOPE      = controls WHO CAN SEE / MANAGE an object (visibility).
    ASSIGNMENT = controls WHO ACTUALLY GETS a role (the matcher/rule).
  These are independent. Do NOT use Scope to control role membership.

  Recommended pattern:  OPEN scope + ENTITY-based ASSIGNMENT.
    - Role is visible/requestable broadly (mobility preserved).
    - Auto-assignment matcher gates membership by entity (no uncontrolled grants).
    - LCM request access can be governed separately by an approval workflow.
-->
<sailpoint>

  <!-- ===== OPTION A : ENTITY-SCOPED (locks mobility - the problem) ===== -->
  <Scope name="BRANCH_A" displayName="Branch A (entity scope)"/>
  <Scope name="BRANCH_B" displayName="Branch B (entity scope)"/>
  <Scope name="BRANCH_C" displayName="Branch C (entity scope)"/>
  <!--
    If LITR-Employee.assignedScope is set to BRANCH_A, only identities/objects
    controlled within BRANCH_A scope can see/manage it. A clerk moving from
    Branch A to Branch B loses visibility. THIS is the mobility breaker.
    (Left here intentionally so the workshop can SHOW the failure mode.)
  -->

  <!-- ===== OPTION B : POPULATIONS for assignment-based gating (the fix) ===== -->
  <!--
    Instead of scoping the role to an entity, leave the role open and let the
    ASSIGNMENT matcher decide membership. Populations make the gating visible
    and reusable in Quicklinks, certifications, and LCM approvals.
  -->
  <GroupDefinition name="pop-Branch-Employees" private="false"
                   displayName="Population - All Branch Employees">
    <Description>Anyone whose entity is a branch. Drives Employee LITR.</Description>
    <GroupFilter>
      <CompositeFilter operation="OR">
        <Filter operation="EQ" property="entity" value="BRANCH_A"/>
        <Filter operation="EQ" property="entity" value="BRANCH_B"/>
        <Filter operation="EQ" property="entity" value="BRANCH_C"/>
      </CompositeFilter>
    </GroupFilter>
  </GroupDefinition>

  <GroupDefinition name="pop-Branch-Managers" private="false"
                   displayName="Population - Branch Managers">
    <Description>Branch identities with isManager = Y. Drives Manager LITR.</Description>
    <GroupFilter>
      <CompositeFilter operation="AND">
        <Filter operation="EQ" property="isManager" value="Y"/>
        <CompositeFilter operation="OR">
          <Filter operation="EQ" property="entity" value="BRANCH_A"/>
          <Filter operation="EQ" property="entity" value="BRANCH_B"/>
          <Filter operation="EQ" property="entity" value="BRANCH_C"/>
        </CompositeFilter>
      </CompositeFilter>
    </GroupFilter>
  </GroupDefinition>

</sailpoint>

### Demo Guide.md

# Branch Access — IIQ Workshop Prototype

A live, importable demo answering the "Proposed Model – Primary Branch Access"
whiteboard. **LITR = Location IT Role**, assigned by Enterprise Entity (EE) /
branch location, and also linkable to a job-function Business Role.

---

## The corrected model: LITR is an IT role with TWO paths onto an identity

| Path | How LITR arrives | IIQ tracks as | Covers |
|---|---|---|---|
| **1. Direct (EE)** | LITR's own assignment selector / rule, matches `entity` | **assigned** | everyone in the branch, incl. external EBC users with no job function |
| **2. Linked (BR)** | a job-function Business Role `requires` the LITR (auto-provisioned) | **required** | identities who get a BR by job function |

The diagram's red arrow (User → Business Role → LITR) is Path 2. The direct
EE assignment straight onto the identity is Path 1. **Both are modeled on
purpose** — see the mover demo below for why.

---

## `permits` vs `requires` — why this demo uses `requires`

- **`requires`** → LITR is **auto-provisioned** when the BR lands. No request,
  no approval. Re-enforced if removed. This is the auto-assignment behaviour.
- **`permitted`** → LITR becomes *requestable* alongside the BR but is **not**
  granted automatically. Someone/workflow must still request it.

Auto-assignment was the goal, so the BR **requires** the LITR. The Branch-A
manager BR shows this statically; `Rule-Link-LITR` shows the scalable variant.

---

## The mover case — the strongest point to make in the room

Marc (Branch A, manager) gets `LITR-Branch-A` by **both** paths at once:
assigned (EE) + required (via the manager BR).

Now Marc stops being a manager but stays in Branch A:
- Path 2 (BR `requires`) **drops** — he's no longer a manager.
- Path 1 (direct EE) **keeps** the LITR — he's still in Branch A.

Net: **Marc keeps his location access across the job change.** Had the LITR
been modeled BR-only, the mover would strip his branch access — a real gap.
The dual path *is* the control that keeps location access stable. Demo it live:
flip `isManager` Y→N for Marc, refresh, show the LITR survives.

---

## One board line to correct before you present

"*Policy is evaluated – based on which the auto assignment rule is triggered.*"
In IIQ these don't chain: **assignment** decides membership during refresh,
**policy** (SOD/risk) inspects the result afterward. Policy never triggers
assignment. (Your notes "assignment = triggering event" and "Manager LITR in
the same rule as Employee LITR" are correct.)

DB analogy for the room: assignment/role scoping = the `WHERE` clause (narrow
vs wide predicate); SOD policy = a `CHECK` constraint on the result. Two
independent things. (No row-security `VIEW` / IIQ Scope object is involved.)

---

## "Scoping" here means ROLE SCOPING, not IIQ Scope objects

The board's mobility-vs-risk debate is about **how narrow or wide the role's
assignment selector is** — the breadth of the matcher predicate — not about
IIQ `Scope` objects (visibility / delegated administration). No `Scope` objects
are in this package on purpose.

| Selector breadth | Control | Mobility |
|---|---|---|
| **Narrow** (`entity = BRANCH_A`) | tight | breaks — mover loses the role |
| **Wide** (`entity IN any branch`) | loose — anyone matching qualifies | preserved |
| **"Current entity"** (per-branch LITR matched to the identity's live `entity`) | tight | preserved — role follows the person on a move |

The third option dissolves the dilemma: stop treating scoping as a fixed entity
lock, treat it as "wherever the person currently is." When the EE attribute
updates on a branch move, the old LITR stops matching and the new one starts —
no broad predicate, no manual re-request. File 02's per-branch LITRs already
implement this; file 04 shows narrow vs wide side by side so the room can see
the failure modes.

---

